[[File:Radical feminist graffit spain.jpg|right|thumb|Feminist stencil graffiti in Spain, 2013: "without you, I am me"]]
'''Female graffiti artists''' are an active part in [[Hip hop#Graffiti|hip hop graffiti]] writing.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lombard|first1=Kara-Jane|title=Men against the wall: Graffiti(ed) masculinities|journal=Journal of Men Studies|volume=21|issue=2013|pages=178‚Äì190}}</ref> Female graffiti artists can face challenges of overt [[sexism]] and sexual assault from fellow artists while executing their work. Examples of female graffiti artists include [[Lady Pink]], Charmin 65, and [[Tatyana Fazlalizadeh]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kelley|first1=Robin D.|title=Yo' Mama's Disfunktional!: Fighting the Culture Wars in Urban America|date=1997|publisher=Beacon Press|location=Boston}}</ref>

Female graffiti writers and street artists use [[Glossary of graffiti|murals, pieces, tags]], and [[street art]] to display their artwork and make their voices heard.

==Sexism in graffiti==
Women tend to be frequently hypersexualized and [[marginalized]] in [[hip hop]], which also extends to the hip hop graffiti subculture.<ref name=":1">{{cite journal|last1=Pab√≥n|first1=Jessica N.|title=The Art of Getting Ovaries: Female Graffiti Artists and the Politics of Presence in Hip Hop's Graffiti Subculture|date=|issue=NYC}}</ref> Female graffiti artists can often be sexualized, tokenized, and marginalized, which scholar Jessica Pab√≥n feels can breed "a culture of misogyny" and can also lead to the oppression of female graffiti artists.<ref name=":1" /> This ideology can also shape how female artists relate to other female writers and how they see themselves as the weaker writer or as a means to gain sexual attention from males.<ref name=":1" />

== Representation in graffiti art ==
Although female writers exist in the [[subculture]] of graffiti, their work tends to be more infrequently seen and acknowledged as that of their male counterparts, something that some artists feel mirrors the lack of [[Femininity|feminine]] representation in the [[art world]].<ref name="Caldwell">{{cite web|url=http://hyperallergic.com/188992/why-arent-women-street-artists-just-street-artists/|title=Why Aren't "Women Street Artists" Just "Street Artists"?|website=Hyperallergic|last1=Caldwell|first1=Caroline|accessdate=9 February 2017}}</ref> As a result, female artists can sometimes voluntary or involuntary become part of the [[Feminist activism in hip hop#Graffiti|feminist movement in graffiti]], as well as the [[feminist art movement]] by bringing their femininity.

==Activism and feminist graffiti communities==
In response to the perceived [[patriarchy]] of graffiti, female graffiti artists in locations such as Chile and Brazil are forming all-female crews where new female artists are given a positive space with support, mentoring and friendship.<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|last=Pab√≥n|first=Jessica|year=2013|title=Be about it: Graffiteras performing feminist community|url=|journal=The Drama Review|volume=3|pages=88‚Äì115|via=}}</ref> These communities feel that by re-claiming space through graffiti they are "[protesting] her invisibility" and "[claiming] space in a subculture where the walls 'belong' to men".<ref name=":0" />

Some female graffiti artists use activism to combat topics such as [[street harassment]], as in the case of street artist [[Tatyana Fazlalizadeh]]'s Stop Telling Women To Smile campaign, which uses posters to empower women and show that catcalling is not acceptable.<ref name="Caldwell" /> Of the campaign, Fazlaizadeh has stated that she wants women to re-claim their public space as "(...) women are not outside on the street for the purpose of entertaining and pleasing men".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Yong|first1=John|title=Street Art to Combat Street Harassment Faced by Women|url=http://designtaxi.com/news/356559/Street-Art-To-%20Combat-Street-Harassment-Faced-By-Women/|date=15 March 2013|website=Designtaxi|accessdate=30 January 2017}}</ref>

